The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Wednesday, March 17, 2004 				 Poll panel set for Bengal recce
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, March 16: A full team of the Election Commission, including T.S. Krishnamurthy, B.B. Tandon and . Gopalaswami, will visit Bengal tomorrow to hear out political parties and take stock of poll preparations.																								We will listen to the political parties and hold discussions with district collectors, superintendents of police and chief secretaries. Later, we will address a press conference, commission spokesperson A.. Jha told a news conference.																								Earlier, a full team of the panel had visited Orissa, Andhra Pradesh and Karnataka. Jha said it would go to Jharkhand and Bihar next week and Maharashtra, Gujarat, Jammu and Kashmir and Uttar Pradesh later.																								The visits are part of the commissions routine pre-poll exercises to tone up the electoral machinery and plug loopholes. Former chief election commissioner J.M. Lyngdoh had made several trips to Jammu and Kashmir before the Assembly polls.																								Trinamul Congress leader Mamata Banerjee had complained to the commission against the Left Front governments rule of terror and intimidation of workers. The party also accused the government of tampering with voters lists. 																								The poll panel, however, believes Bengals lists are quite clean. Trinamul is likely to raise the same allegations before the commission tomorrow.																								The commission has also lined up a series of meetings on Delhis poll preparations. It will brief 1,500 general observers and 750 expenditure observers on Friday and Saturday. 																								Expenditure observers will keep a strict watch on candidates accounts. General observers are IAS officers chosen from different parts of the country.																								The observers are the eyes and ears of the commission. They are our direct contact with the field mechanism, Jha said. He added that observers have adequate powers to intervene in the polls  even at the time of counting  if they notice any irregularity. 																								They are expected to bring to the notice of the panel any incidents of violence or booth capturing on election day, Jha said. 
